<section id="career">
  <h2>Career &amp; Strengths</h2>
  <p>The Tiger's combination of courage, leadership instinct, and competitive drive makes them naturally suited to high-stakes roles where decisive action and personal authority are valued.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Military &amp; Defence</strong> — The Tiger's courage and strategic instinct find their most classical expression in military leadership</li>
    <li><strong>Leadership &amp; Executive Roles</strong> — Natural authority and the confidence to make difficult decisions under pressure</li>
    <li><strong>Athletics &amp; Competition</strong> — Thrives in competitive environments where physical or mental prowess is tested</li>
    <li><strong>Performing Arts</strong> — Magnetic stage presence and the ability to captivate audiences with raw energy</li>
    <li><strong>Law Enforcement &amp; Justice</strong> — Strong sense of right and wrong paired with the courage to enforce it</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="culture">
  <h2>Cultural Significance</h2>
  <p>The Tiger is regarded as the <strong>King of Beasts</strong> (百獸之王) in Chinese tradition — a role the lion holds in Western culture. The character "王" (king) is said to be visible in the markings on the tiger's forehead, and this association with royal authority pervades Chinese art, literature, and folk religion.</p>
  <p>Tiger imagery serves as a powerful protective talisman in Chinese folk culture. Children wear tiger-head shoes (虎頭鞋) and tiger-head hats (虎頭帽) to ward off evil spirits and illness. The Door Gods (門神) of many households are depicted with tiger companions. In traditional medicine and feng shui, the White Tiger (白虎) represents the western direction and the metal element, balancing the Azure Dragon of the east. The phrase "虎虎生威" (the tiger generates awe) captures the animal's cultural role as a symbol of power, courage, and protective authority.</p>
</section>
